classes.title: CALC W/ ALG & TRIG
classes.description: Math 3B with precalculus: A continued review of relevant topics from precal culus (see Math 2A); integral calculus, including definite and indefinite i ntegrals; techniques of integration, introduction to sequences and series; with applications in mathematics and physics.

classes.title: CALC WITH APPLI 1
classes.description: Differential Calculus including analytic geometry, functions and limits, de rivatives, techniques and applications of   differentiation; introduction t o integration; logarithmic and trigonometric functions.

classes.title: CALC WITH APPLI 2
classes.description: Integral calculus including definite and indefinite integrals, techniques o f integration; introduction to sequences and series; with applications in m athematics and physics.

classes.title: LIN ALG W/APPS
classes.description: Systems of linear equations, matrix algebra, determinants, vector spaces an d subspaces, basis and dimension, linear transformations, eigenvalues and e igenvectors, diagonalization, and orthogonality.

classes.title: DIFF EQUATIONS
classes.description: First and second order differential equations, separation of variables, lin ear differential equations, systems of first order equations, nonlinear dif ferential equations and stability.

classes.title: VECTOR CALCULUS 1
classes.description: Calculus of functions of several variables, vector valued functions of one variable, derivative and integrals of vector functions, double and triple i ntegrals, properties and applications of integrals, change of variables.

classes.title: VECTOR CALCULUS 2
classes.description: Scalar and vector fields, integration along paths, integration over surface s and solid regions, integral theorems of vector calculus, Fourier series, partial differential equations.

classes.title: TRANS HIGHER MATH
classes.description: Introduction to the elements of propositional logic,   techniques of mathem atical proof, and fundamental mathematical   structures, including sets, fu nctions, relations, and other   topics as time permits. Mastery of this mat erial is essential   for students planning to major in mathematics.

classes.title: CALC FOR SOCIAL SCI
classes.description: Introduction to differential and integral calculus with   applications to m odeling in the biological sciences.

classes.title: CALC-SOC & LIFE SCI
classes.description: Continued study of differential and integral calculus with   differential a ndintegral calculus with applications.   Introduction to mathematical model ing with differential   equations. Calculus of several variables including an introduction to partial derivatives.

classes.title: CLASSICAL NO SYSTEM
classes.description: A conceptual rather than an axiomatic development starting with the natural numbers and progressing through the integral, rational, real, and complex number systems. The historical implications of these developments in number systems. Especially suitable for prospective middle and high school teache rs.

classes.title: MOD EUCL & NONEUCL
classes.description: Topics in plane and solid geometry. The axioms of pure, euclidean, projecti ve, and noneuclidean geometry. Transformational geometry (isometries, dilit ations, involutions, perspectivities, and projectivities). The history and the historical implications of these developments in geometry. Especially s uitable for prospective middle and high school teachers.

classes.title: INTRO NUM ANALYSIS
classes.description: Numerical methods for the solution of nonlinear equations   (Newton method) , for integration (quadrature formulas and composite   integration), and fo r the initial value problem for ordinary differential   equations (Euler an d Kutta methods).

classes.title: NUMERICAL ANALYSIS
classes.description: Numerical methods for the solution of systems of linear   equations (direct and iteractive methods), and the finite   difference methods for boundary value problems for   (ordinary and partial) differential equations.

classes.title: INTRO TO LINEAR ALG
classes.description: Abstract vector spaces and subspaces. Span and linear independence. Basis a nd dimension. Linear maps. Eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

classes.title: ADV LINEAR ALG
classes.description: Diagonalization, inner product spaces, projections, least-  squares approxi mations, invariant factors and elementary   divisors, canonical forms, topi cs from advanced matrix   theory, applied linear algebra, and group represe ntation   theory.

classes.title: ABSTRACT ALGEBRA
classes.description: Rings, fields, Galois theory.

classes.title: INTRO NUMBER THEORY
classes.description: Divisibility, congruences, primitive roots an indices, quadratic residues and the   quadratic reciprocity law, number-theoretic functions, Diophantine equations,   the distribution of primes, number-theorhetic methods in cryptography,   quadratic forms, continued fractions, and the approximation of real numbers,   algebraic number theory, partitions.

classes.title: COMB ANALYSIS
classes.description: Elementary counting principles, binomial coefficients, generating functions,   recurrence relations, the principle of inclusion and exclusion, distributions and   partitions, systems of distinct representatives, applications to computation.

classes.title: METHODS OF ANALYSIS
classes.description: Introduction to methods of proof in analysis. topics include limits, sequen ces   and series, continuity, compactness, as well as other topics. This co urse is   intended to follow Mathematics 8 and to introduce students to the level of   sophistication of upper-division mathematics.

classes.title: INTRO REAL ANALYSIS
classes.description: The real number system, elements of set theory, continuity,   differentiabi lity, Riemann integral, implicit function   theorems, convergence processes , and special topics.

classes.title: CHAO DYN & BIFU THE
classes.description: Hyperbolic structure and chaos; center manifolds; bifurcation theory; and t he Feigenbaum and Ruelle-Takens cascades to strange attractors.

classes.title: INTRO COMPLX VARIAB
classes.description: Complex numbers, functions, differentiability, series   extensions of eleme ntary functions, complex integration,   calculus of residues, conformal map s, mapping functions,   applications.

classes.title: PART DIFF EQUATIONS
classes.description: Wave, heat, and potential equations.

classes.title: INTRO OPER RESEARCH
classes.description: Linear programming, the simplex method, duality, applications   to the tran sportation and assignment problems, sensitivity   analysis, problem formula tion.

classes.title: INTERN IN MATH
classes.description: Faculty sponsored academic internship in industrial or research firms.

classes.title: SENIOR THESIS
classes.description: Independent research under the supervision of a faculty member which will result in a senior thesis. Student will concentrate on reading and gathering material for a thesis.

classes.title: SENIOR THESIS
classes.description: Independent research under the supervision of a faculty member which will result in a senior thesis. Student will concentrate on writing a thesis.

classes.title: INDEPENDENT STUDIES
classes.description: Coursework consists of academic research supervised by a faculty member on a topic not available in established course offerings.

classes.title: IND RES ASSIST MATH
classes.description: Coursework consists of faculty supervised research assistance.
